[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Putting It All Together
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Here's the full pipeline assembled into a single function. This is what your Step Functions state machine would orchestrate, or what you'd call for a batch processing run.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def process_literature_batch(last_watermark: str, max_articles: int = 50) -> dict:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Run the full literature-to-knowledge-graph pipeline for a batch of articles.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     This is the main entry point. In production, EventBridge would trigger
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     this on a schedule (daily or hourly), and Step Functions would orchestrate
